programmes.show_description: Forward Base: Steed, Purdey, and Gambit investigate some rather strange events centred around Lake Ontario. Could a stolen piece of technology be the cause of these bizarre events?
Mission... Highly Improbable: The Avengers investigate when a car carrying Ministry officials to a meeting mysteriously disappears. Is the case linked to shrinking budgets?
Dear Dad... Again: Hawkeye pens a letter to his father, detailing the day-to-day insanity of living in the camp, including a bet with Trapper that nobody will notice if Hawkeye dines naked.
The Longjohn Flap: In the middle of a cold snap, Hawkeye receives a pair of long-johns from home. Hawkeye gives them to an ill Trapper out of sympathy and he loses them in a poker game.
The Army-Navy Game: Excitement runs high in the camp on the day of the Army/Navy football game, with several members of the 4077th putting money into a betting pool.
The Restaurant: An exhibition of ethnic masks hardly seems like the perfect location for a date, but Laura and Mike are simply trying to avoid attending another party.
An uplifting round-up of good news stories from the UK and around the world.
Basinger's New York: It's Christmas and Jonathan and Mark's assignment is to show a cynical columnist named Basinger that there's still some good out there.
An uplifting round-up of good news stories from the UK and around the world.
All That Glitters: When a major fire threatens a neighbourhood, Jonathan and Mark, in the guise of priests, re-open an abandoned church as a shelter.
An uplifting round-up of good news stories from the UK and around the world.

An uplifting round-up of good news stories from the UK and around the world.
The Hero: Joe Mason, a Vietnam veteran, tries to get government assistance with expensive dental work, however, because his condition is not related to his military service, he is denied.
Parents' Day: Ronald James, a respected newsman and anti-drug advocate, is shocked to come home and find out that his son has turned him into the police for cocaine addiction.
Days Of Sunshine, Days Of Shadow: Part 1: The marriage between Almonzo and Laura faces a test when he falls seriously ill with pneumonia. Part 1 of 2.
An uplifting round-up of good news stories from the UK and around the world.
Days Of Sunshine, Days Of Shadow: Part 2: Almonzo's continued negative outlook on life during his recovery from a stroke takes its toll on the Wilder marriage. Part 2 of 2.
The Wingwalker: Death-Defying Bobby Storm, a beautiful, young stuntwoman, offers her dangerously troubled heart to John-Boy Walton.
The Competition: Olivia Walton and her daughter, Erin, must face intense life challenges when forced to give up newfound love relationships.
Stardust in Your Eyes: Quigley is about to pull off the deal of his life, but first he has to impress a group of Korean businessmen with some Irish nostalgia.
The Inspector Calls: The whole village rallies together when Ormston is struck by two crises. Can they raise enough money to pass a hospital inspection?
Secrecy: In the middle of an emergency at a remote farmhouse, Dr Finlay comes into contact with the reclusive James Geddie. An attempt to know more about Geddie leads to a macabre discovery.
Rumpole and the Right to Silence: A college professor accused of murder uses his 'right to silence' by refusing to disclose his alibi to the court. Can Rumpole come to his defence?
Sticky Wicket: Hawkeye becomes overly concerned when his patient fails to improve after surgery. Frank taunts Hawkeye by calling him 'Super Surgeon' which prompts a fight.
Major Fred C Dobbs: Hawkeye's and Trapper's latest scheme succeeds when Frank and Hot Lips demand a transfer to another unit, but they soon realise that they will have to work double shifts.
Ceasefire: News of a ceasefire has reached the 4077th. Everyone celebrates and says their good-byes, except Trapper, who remains skeptical. Hawkeye still has gambling debts to settle.
...Likely Lads?: The Go-Between: Bob becomes more and more depressed by Thelma's absence and Terry's housekeeping. Finally, Terry can take no more and leaves him as well.
...Likely Lads?: Conduct Unbecoming: When faced with a fight, Terry has a golden rule: 'Do unto others as they would do unto you - but do it first.'
...Likely Lads?: The Shape of Things to Come: The death of disreputable old Uncle Jacob is received by the Collier family with a mixture of regret and relief.
The Gladiators: The team investigate the mysterious disappearance of Soviet and Canadian agents. They soon unearth a criminal plot which could lead to the destabilisation of Canada.
The Forget-Me-Knot: Trainee agent Tara King joins Steed as they search for a traitor within the organisation. Mrs. Peel leaves the team when her missing husband reappears.

Wally: Jonathan and Mark's latest assignment is Wally, a lovable elderly hobo and street puppeteer who's caring and good nature have made him, without his knowing it, an angel.
An uplifting round-up of good news stories from the UK and around the world.
A Song Of Songs: Gabe Wilson, an old friend of Mark's, tries to re-build his life after suffering a heart attack. He is reunited with his old flame but finds out she has changed.

A Father's Faith: During their time off, Jonathan and Mark visit an old friend whose livelihood is in jeopardy due to the amount of time he devotes to his comatose son.
Heavy Date: A young man with no particular direction in life has a breakdown after finding out that the girl he is in love with is pregnant.
A Faraway Cry: Caroline travels to an influenza-ridden mining camp with Dr Baker after she receives a plea for help from an old friend who is pregnant and desperately ill.
He Was Only Twelve: Part 1: During a trip to Sleepy Eye, James and Albert walk into a bank robbery. James is critically wounded, and the doctor tells James is expected to die. Part 1 of 2.
He Was Only Twelve: Part 2: Charles, unable to deal with the mounting pressure concerning his son's critical condition, becomes verbally abusive to his family and friends. Part 2 of 2.
The Emergence: The Walton children learn that it is not easy having their mother as a substitute teacher, and John-Boy rediscovers a former girlfriend.
The Loss: When a young widow comes to stay in their home, the Walton children learn a hard lesson about how to cope with another person's grief.
The Fortune in Men's Eyes: Ambrose's mother, Imelda, returns to look after baby Kieran. Quigley takes an unusual interest in her, much to Ambrose's dismay.
Buried Treasure: Tom is shocked when a patient's husband refuses medical treatment for his wife. Michael finds ancient coins during a treasure hunt.
In Arcadia: Preparations and celebrations for Janet and Angus's wedding are underway, but Dr Cameron feels increasingly isolated. Dr Finlay is drawn toward the new National Health Service.
Rumpole at Sea: Rumpole is faced with a mystery whilst holidaying on a cruise with Hilda. Can he uncover the truth behind the disappearance of a missing passenger?
Showtime: Hawkeye and Frank clash as usual over the treatment of a soldier. Trapper fights desperately to save a badly injured man. He asks Mulcahy to pray for his surgical skills.
Divided We Stand: Captain Philip Hildebrand, an Army psychiatrist, is sent to investigate the 4077th for mental breakdowns. He informs Colonel Blake that his presence should be kept a secret.
5 O'Clock Charlie: A North Korean pilot makes his daily attempt to bomb the ammo dump but always misses and the whole business has become something of a spectator sport.
